{"findings":[{"id":"F-001","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Legacy mint accounting overissues cTokens for fee-on-transfer deposits","locations":["0x3d9819210a31b4961b30ef54be2aed79b9c9cd3b/Contract.sol:1492","0x3d9819210a31b4961b30ef54be2aed79b9c9cd3b/Contract.sol:1521","0x3d9819210a31b4961b30ef54be2aed79b9c9cd3b/Contract.sol:1552","0x3d9819210a31b4961b30ef54be2aed79b9c9cd3b/Contract.sol:2361"],"claim":"The legacy flattened CToken mints against the user-supplied `mintAmount`, but its abstract `doTransferIn` hook only returns an error code and cannot report how much underlying was actually received. A fee-on-transfer or deflationary underlying therefore lets the market mint cTokens as if the full amount arrived even when less cash was credited.","impact":"If such an underlying is listed through this legacy implementation, an attacker can mint excess cTokens against underfunded deposits and later redeem or borrow against claims that are not backed by real cash, diluting suppliers and potentially draining the market.","paths":["mint -> mintFresh computes `mintTokens` from `mintAmount` -> `doTransferIn(minter, mintAmount)` receives less than `mintAmount` -> attacker receives cTokens backed by insufficient cash"],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-002","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Legacy repay path clears debt using the nominal amount instead of cash actually received","locations":["0x3d9819210a31b4961b30ef54be2aed79b9c9cd3b/Contract.sol:1862","0x3d9819210a31b4961b30ef54be2aed79b9c9cd3b/Contract.sol:1903","0x3d9819210a31b4961b30ef54be2aed79b9c9cd3b/Contract.sol:1924","0x3d9819210a31b4961b30ef54be2aed79b9c9cd3b/Contract.sol:2361"],"claim":"In the legacy flattened CToken, `repayBorrowFresh` subtracts `vars.repayAmount` from both borrower principal and `totalBorrows` before/without learning the actual amount transferred in. Because `doTransferIn` only signals success or failure, short transfers are still accounted as full repayments.","impact":"A borrower using a taxed/deflationary underlying can extinguish more debt than they actually repay, then withdraw collateral or leave the market with bad debt that honest suppliers absorb.","paths":["repayBorrow/repayBorrowBehalf -> repayBorrowFresh sets `vars.repayAmount` -> debt and `totalBorrows` are reduced by that nominal amount -> `doTransferIn(payer, vars.repayAmount)` delivers less cash than was credited"],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-003","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Legacy liquidation over-seizes collateral from the requested repay amount","locations":["0x3d9819210a31b4961b30ef54be2aed79b9c9cd3b/Contract.sol:1975","0x3d9819210a31b4961b30ef54be2aed79b9c9cd3b/Contract.sol:2008","0x3d9819210a31b4961b30ef54be2aed79b9c9cd3b/Contract.sol:2019","0x3d9819210a31b4961b30ef54be2aed79b9c9cd3b/Contract.sol:2361"],"claim":"The legacy liquidation flow computes `seizeTokens` from the caller-supplied `repayAmount` before repayment occurs, and the same legacy repay path cannot distinguish nominal from actual transferred value. On fee-on-transfer borrow assets, collateral is therefore priced from an amount the market never actually received.","impact":"A liquidator can repay less value than assumed yet seize full collateral, directly stealing borrower collateral and worsening protocol insolvency.","paths":["liquidateBorrow -> liquidateBorrowFresh computes `seizeTokens` from `repayAmount` -> `repayBorrowFresh` accounts full `repayAmount` even if less cash arrives -> collateral seizure executes using inflated `seizeTokens`"],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-004","severity":"Medium","confidence":"medium","title":"Missing `maxAssets` enforcement allows asset-list bloat to gas-grief liquidity checks","locations":["0xbafe01ff935c7305907c33bf824352ee5979b526/contracts/ComptrollerStorage.sol:48","0xbafe01ff935c7305907c33bf824352ee5979b526/contracts/Comptroller.sol:127","0xbafe01ff935c7305907c33bf824352ee5979b526/contracts/Comptroller.sol:139","0xbafe01ff935c7305907c33bf824352ee5979b526/contracts/Comptroller.sol:352","0xbafe01ff935c7305907c33bf824352ee5979b526/contracts/Comptroller.sol:722"],"claim":"`maxAssets` is documented as a cap on how many markets an account can join, but neither `enterMarkets` nor `addToMarketInternal` enforces it. As a result, `accountAssets[account]` can grow without bound, and every borrow, redeem, transfer, and non-deprecated liquidation liquidity check must iterate the entire array in `getHypotheticalAccountLiquidityInternal`.","impact":"If enough markets are listed, an attacker can deliberately bloat their asset list with dust positions until liquidity checks become prohibitively expensive, which can block further risk checks and make unhealthy positions impractical to liquidate, leading to permissionless bad-debt accumulation.","paths":["user enters many markets via `enterMarkets` or auto-entry on first borrow -> `accountAssets[user]` grows unbounded -> liquidation/borrow/redeem/transfer checks iterate all entries in `getHypotheticalAccountLiquidityInternal` -> calls can run out of practical gas"],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-006","severity":"Medium","confidence":"high","title":"`fixBadAccruals` records COMP debt that future claims never honor","locations":["0xbafe01ff935c7305907c33bf824352ee5979b526/contracts/Comptroller.sol:1089","0xbafe01ff935c7305907c33bf824352ee5979b526/contracts/Comptroller.sol:1117","0xbafe01ff935c7305907c33bf824352ee5979b526/contracts/Comptroller.sol:1341","0xbafe01ff935c7305907c33bf824352ee5979b526/contracts/Comptroller.sol:1360","0xbafe01ff935c7305907c33bf824352ee5979b526/contracts/Comptroller.sol:1371"],"claim":"`fixBadAccruals` records overpaid rewards in `compReceivable`, but later COMP claims only look at `compAccrued` and `grantCompInternal`. No claim path offsets, blocks, or collects against `compReceivable` before sending new COMP.","impact":"Users marked as owing COMP can continue claiming newly accrued rewards normally, so mistaken COMP distributions remain unrecoverable on-chain and the intended remediation does not actually restore protocol funds.","paths":["admin calls `fixBadAccruals` -> `compReceivable[user]` increases -> user later calls `claimComp` -> `grantCompInternal` transfers full newly accrued COMP without netting the receivable"],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]}],"rejected_candidates":[{"title":"Borrow and redeem paths expose stale-liquidity reentrancy across markets","source_agents":["codex_1"],"reason":"Only the abstract base contracts are in scope here; no concrete `doTransferOut` implementation is present that shows an attacker-controlled callback path. Without a concrete market implementation that can reenter, the claim is too speculative to report."},{"title":"Close Factor Not Validated on _setCloseFactor","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"This is an admin-only parameter-setting path. Any harm depends on privileged misconfiguration by the trusted admin, which is not a standalone protocol vulnerability in this codebase."},{"title":"Oracle Price Manipulation Risk","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"The report describes the trusted admin's ability to replace the oracle. That is a governance/control assumption, not an exploitable bug by unprivileged actors."},{"title":"No Timelock on Critical Admin Functions","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Absence of a timelock is a governance design choice rather than a code vulnerability. The candidate does not identify an unprivileged exploit path."},{"title":"Liquidation Incentive Not Validated","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"This is another admin-only misconfiguration scenario. Since the same admin can already make broader privileged changes, the missing bound is not a distinct reportable vulnerability here."},{"title":"Interest Rate Model Can Be Changed Instantly","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Changing the interest rate model is an intended admin power guarded by `msg.sender == admin` plus interface checks. This is governance trust, not a protocol bug."},{"title":"Comptroller Can Be Changed on CTokens","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"`_setComptroller` is an explicit admin hook and verifies the new target implements the comptroller marker. The candidate is a generic privileged-upgrade concern, not a vulnerability."},{"title":"Borrow Cap Guardian Can Disable Borrowing","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"The claim is factually incorrect for this code: `_setMarketBorrowCaps` documents and implements `0` as unlimited borrowing, not disabled borrowing. More generally, borrow-cap setting is an intended privileged control."},{"title":"COMP Accrual Fix Function Allows Arbitrary Adjustment","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"The function is a one-off admin-only remediation hook and the candidate relies on trusted-admin abuse. The reportable issue in this area is instead that recorded `compReceivable` debt is never enforced."},{"title":"Unitroller Delegatecall Reentrancy Risk","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"This is the standard upgradeable proxy delegation pattern. The candidate does not show a distinct exploit beyond compromising the trusted implementation/admin path."},{"title":"Market Deprecation Can Be Abused for Immediate Liquidation","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"`isDeprecated` is an explicit admin-controlled deprecation mechanism. The ability to deprecate a market is an intended governance action, not an accidental bypass."},{"title":"Pause Guardian Can Pause Critical Functions","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"The pause guardian is an intentional emergency-control role documented in storage comments. This is a trust/governance feature, not a bug."}]}
